Neural Networks and Deep Learning¶

In a previous exercise, you built your own simple neural network (perceptron) and implemented the gradient descent optimizer. Hopefully that helped you build some intuition of how a neural network learns. The perceptron is a very simple model, and thus quite limited in its application. More complicated tasks require more sophisticated optimizers, cost functions as well as network architectures.

This week, we will use the python deep learning library Keras and learn how to build a basic neural network with it. These exercises have been adapted from the tensorflow tutorial as well as the book Deep Learning with Python by François Chalet.

In the first part of this notebook, you'll find a fully worked through example of the classic machine learning problem of handwritten digit classification. This should prepare you for the first exercise, where you will tackle a very similar problem — the classification of articles of clothing.

In the second exercise, we move to another common type of problem: a regression problem. You will use the Boston Housing Price dataset and try to predict the median price of homes in a given Boston suburb.

These introductory problems are intentionally kept brief and rather simple. The main goal of this week is for you to get a taste of how to tackle common machine learning problems and develop a good workflow that can easily be adapted for other, more elaborate problems.

After this exercise, you will be able to

  • solve simple image classification & regression tasks with keras
  • employ cross-validation to estimate the validation error

Keywords: neural networks: deep learning, keras, activation function, optimzer, loss function — image classification: handwritten digits, clothing — regression: house prices — cross validation

A first look at a neural network¶

Let's look at a fully-worked through example of a neural network built in Keras. The problem we will solve is a machine learning classic: classification of handwritten digits with the MNIST dataset.

First, let's define the problem: We are trying to solve the classification of grayscale images of handwritten digits (28 x 28 pixels) into 10 categories (one through nine). In a grayscale image, each point in the two dimensional space has two values (a, b) assigned to it, where a and b range of 0 to 255. Or to put it simply, the pixel values fall in the range of 0 to 255. We begin by loading the dataset.

For humans, it's very easy to correctly identify the above picture as a '4'. Actually, it will just require a few lines of code to train a neural network to be quite good at this task, as well. The first step of this (after loading the data) is to build the network.

In [10]:
network = keras.models.Sequential()
network.add(keras.layers.Dense(512, activation="relu", input_shape=(28 * 28,)))
network.add(keras.layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax"))

The basic building block is the layer, and the network above consists of fully connected (dense) layers. The first layer has 512 neurons assigned to it. You can think of the first layer as a function that takes a 2D tensor (28 x 28) as an input and returns another tensor. To be more precise, it performs the relu tensor operation $relu(Z) = max(Z, 0)$, where $Z = W \cdot X + b$. Here, $X$ is the input tensor and $W$ and $b$ are the weights and are properties of the layer. The second layer is a 10-way softmax layer, meaning it will return an array of 10 probability scores. Take a moment and think about what shapes $X, W$ and $b$ are in this specific example.

The network's layers are now defined, but we still need to assign three very important properties: a loss function, an optimizer and metrics to monitor during training and testing.

In [11]:
network.compile(optimizer="rmsprop", loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])

Before proceeding, we should pre-process the data a bit by reshaping it into the shape the network expects. In the first layer from above, we assigned it an input shape of (28 * 28), meaning we need to flatten the training and test data. Also, we will scale the data so that all values are in the [0, 1] interval.

In [12]:
train_images = train_images.reshape((60000, 28 * 28))  # reshape the training data
train_images = train_images.astype("float32") / 255  # normalize the training data (255 = max rgb(?) num) -> each pixel [0,1]

test_images = test_images.reshape((10000, 28 * 28))  # rehsape the test data
test_images = test_images.astype("float32") / 255  # normalize the test data

Another requirement is that the labels need to be encoded categorically. Categorical encoding (also called one-hot encoding) embeds each label as a vector with all coefficients set to zero except with a one at the label index. What should the shape of the encoded training labels be?

It is quite common for the test accuracy to be lower than the training accuracy. This is one example of overfitting, demonstrating that neural networks in general tend to perform worse on test data.

The network is trained and evaluated, it can now be used to make predictions about some images. The prediction will be an array of 10 confidence values of the model that correspond to the digits from 0 to 9.

The helper functions below make it possible to easily look at a bunch of images and the associated predictions.

In [35]:
cmap = mpl.cm.get_cmap("Paired")
col_true = cmap(1)
col_false = cmap(5)


def plot_image(i, predictions_array, true_label, img):
    """ Plot an image and sets the x-label
    to the predicted class.
    
    Args:
    i (int) :: index to select an item from 
               prediction_array, true_label and img
    predictions_array (array) :: predicted labels
    true_label (array) :: true labels
    img (array) :: image to be plotted
    """
    assert isinstance(i, int)
    predictions_array, true_label, img = predictions_array[i], true_label[i], img[i]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

    plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.binary)

    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)
    if predicted_label == true_label:
        color = col_true
    else:
        color = col_false

    plt.xlabel(
        "{} {:2.0f}% ({})".format(
            class_names[predicted_label],
            100 * np.max(predictions_array),
            class_names[true_label],
        ),
        color=color,
    )


def plot_value_array(i, predictions_array, true_label):
    """ Create a bar plot of the predictions.
    
    Args:
    i (int) :: index to select an item from
               predictions_array and true_label
    predictions_array (array) :: predicted labels
    true_labels (array) :: true labels
    """
    assert isinstance(i, int)
    predictions_array, true_label = predictions_array[i], true_label[i]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    thisplot = plt.bar(range(10), predictions_array, color="#777777")
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)

    thisplot[predicted_label].set_color(col_false)
    thisplot[true_label].set_color(col_true)

Regression with neural networks: predicting house prices¶

The two previous examples were classification problems, meaning the goal was to predict a single discrete label as a function of an input. Another common type of problem in machine learning is when the algorithm should predict a continuous value — these are regression problems. You've already seen them in previous weeks.

The second exercise focuses on regression with neural networks. You will use the Boston Housing Price dataset and attempt to predict the median price of homes in a given Boston suburb in the mid-1970s. As an input, you will have data about, for example, local property tax or crime rate.

Again, the dataset can be loaded with keras. You have a number of training/test samples, each with some numerical features, such as per capita crime rate, average number of rooms per house, and so on. The target arrays hold the median values of owner-occupied homes, measured in thousands of USD (houses were cheap in the 70s). We are also creating a dataframe from the training data that can be used to create pair plots.

In [2]:
(train_data, train_targets),(test_data, test_targets) = keras.datasets.boston_housing.load_data()

training_data = np.append(train_data, train_targets.reshape(train_data.shape[0], -1), axis=1)
df = pd.DataFrame(training_data)

Recall that the feature scaling is transforming the features like so: $\tilde{x} = (x - \mu) / \sigma$. When standardizing the data, be careful that you calculate the mean/standard deviation along the right axis. Also standardize the test data using the quantities calculated from the training data. It is important to never use quantities computed on the test data.

In [4]:
# to-do: standardize the data
mu = train_data.mean(axis=0)
sd = train_data.std(axis=0)

train_data -= mu
train_data /= sd

test_data -= mu
test_data /= sd

As you've seen above, there are only few samples available. You'll use a quite small network with two hidden layers, each with 64 neurons, and one output layer with only a single neuron. This is common practice when you are trying to predict a single value, as is the case here. We don't want to add an activation function at the last layer because that will constrain the output to a certain range (think of the sigmoid function). Your last layer should have a single neuron corresponding to the prediction. All the layers are fully (densely) connected. For the activation function, you can use "relu" again.

When you compile the model, you can use the same optimizer as in the first example. For the loss, you should use the mean squared error ("mse"), while the metric is the mean absolute error (["mae"]). This is the absolute value of the difference between predictions and targets.

Here's a summary of the network:

  • 1st layer: dense layer with 64 neurons using the "relu" activation function with the appropriate input_shape specified.
  • 2nd layer: dense layer with 64 neurons using the "relu" activation function.
  • 3rd layer: dense layer with 1 neuron, no activation function.
  • Optimizer: "rmsprop", loss: "mse", metrics: ["mae"]

Here's how the build_model function should look like: ``` def build_model(): model = keras.models.Sequential() model.add(keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(train_data.shape[1],))) model.add(keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')) model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1)) model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss='mse', metrics=['mae']) return model ```

In [5]:
# to-do: complete the function that builds & compiles the network
def build_model():
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    # to-do: add layers and compile the model
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(64, activation="relu", input_shape=(train_data.shape[1],)))
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(64, activation="relu"))
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1))

    model.compile(optimizer="rmsprop", loss="mse", metrics=["mae"])
    return model

The network architecture is defined, let's proceed by training and evaluating the model.

Since the dataset is quite small, we can use the k-fold cross-validation method to split the available training data into partial training and validation sets. This can be done by calling model_selection.KFold(n_splits=k) from sklearn.

When fitting the model, also pass the two additional arguments batch_size=1 and verbose=0 to the fit method. batch_size is the number of samples per gradient update, and verbose=0 stops the output from appearing in your console.

In [10]:
# to-do: create the k-fold splits
kf = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=4)
kf.get_n_splits(train_data)

# to-do: train and evaluate the model on the splits
test_scores = []
num_epochs = 50

i = 1
for train_idx, val_idx in kf.split(train_data):
    print("processing fold #", i)
    # to-do: implement the training/evaluation loop
    model = build_model()
    history = model.fit(x=train_data[train_idx], y=train_targets[train_idx],
        validation_data=(train_data[val_idx], train_targets[val_idx]),
        epochs=num_epochs, verbose=0)
    
    # and store the mae in test_scores
    test_scores.append(history.history["val_mae"])
    # remember that you have to build a new model at
    # each iteration step
    i += 1

print("Test scores:", test_scores)
print("Mean test score: {:.4f}".format(np.mean(test_scores)))

As you can see, the different runs can show quite different validation scores. That's why cross-validation yields a much better estimate for the validation error.

In the next step, you can try at least 200 (up to 500) epochs, depending on how much time you have (and how powerful your computer is). At each k-fold iteration, store the mae history in all_mae_histories.

In [11]:
# to-do: modified training/validation loop
kf = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=4)
kf.get_n_splits(train_data)

all_mae_histories = []
num_epochs = 200

i = 1
for train_idx, val_idx in kf.split(train_data):
    print("processing fold #", i)
    # to-do: implement the training/evaluation loop
    model = build_model()
    history = model.fit(x=train_data[train_idx], y=train_targets[train_idx],
        validation_data=(train_data[val_idx], train_targets[val_idx]),
        epochs=num_epochs, verbose=0)
    # hint:
    # assign your model to a variable, e.g.,
    # history = model.fit(X, Y, validation_data=(X_val, Y_val), **kwargs)
    # then you can get the mae history with
    # history.history['val_mae']
    # note that written like this, the fit method also evaluates the model
    # automatically
    all_mae_histories.append(history.history["val_mae"])
    i += 1

It's a little difficult to see a trend because of issues with scaling and the high variance. We can try the smoothing with the following function (exponential moving average of the previous points) and omitting the first 10 epochs.

In [15]:
def smooth_curve(points, factor=0.9):
    smoothed_points = []
    for point in points:
        if smoothed_points:
            previous = smoothed_points[-1]
            smoothed_points.append(previous * factor + point * (1 - factor))
        else:
            smoothed_points.append(point)
    return smoothed_points
